  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And thou shall put them on Aaron thy brother, and his sons with him,.... And this putting on of their garments by Moses, under the authority of God, was a solemn investiture of them with the priestly office also; for from henceforward they had a right to exercise it, having those garments on, without which they were never to officiate: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and shall anoint them; with the anointing oil, of which afterwards a particular account is given, and how to be made, and for what use, Exodus 30:22, typical of the holy graces of the Spirit of God: ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and shall anoint them; with the anointing oil, of which afterwards a particular account is given, and how to be made, and for what use, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Exodus 30:22",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", typical of the holy graces of the Spirit of God: ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and consecrate them; the consecration of them was by investing them with their garments, and by anointing them with oil; for this phrase does not intend the whole of their consecration, only another branch of it, and may be literally rendered, \"fill their hand\" (p); that is, with sacrifices to be offered up by them, see Exodus 29:1. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and consecrate them; the consecration of them was by investing them with their garments, and by anointing them with oil; for this phrase does not intend the whole of their consecration, only another branch of it, and may be literally rendered, \"fill their hand\" (p); that is, with sacrifices to be offered up by them, see ",
            "children": []
